ns. But what does “closure” really mean for those who survive-or lose loved ones in-traumatic acts? In the wake of such terrifying events, is closure a realistic or appropriate expectation? In Killing McVeigh, Jody Lyneé Madeira uses the Oklahoma City bombing as a case study to explore how family members and other survivors come to terms with mass murder. As the fullest case study to date of the Oklahoma City Bombing survivors’ struggle for justice and the first-ever case study of closure, this book describes the profound human and institutional impacts of these labors to demonstrate the importance of understanding what closure really is before naively asserting it can or has been reached.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCapital punishmentzUnited StatesvCases. 0aCapital punishmentzUnited StatesxPsychological aspects. 0aDomestic terrorismxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aDomestic terrorismzUnited StatesxPsychological aspects. 0aOklahoma City Federal Building Bombing, Oklahoma City, Okla., 1995xPsychological aspects. 0aTerrorism victims' familiesxPsychology. 0aVictims of terrorismxPsychology. 0aVictims of terrorismxRehabilitationzUnited States. 0aVictims of terrorismxRehabilitation. 0aVictims of terrorismzUnited StatesxPsychology. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081479610840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814724545423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814724545/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMA